Share this...FacebookTwitterGerman business daily Handelsblatt here reports on a new study that suggests up to 114,000 German automotive related jobs could disappear should the switchover to electric mobility take place as planned.
According to research by the German Labor Market and Occupational Research Institute (IAB) and its publication titled â€œElectric Mobility 2035â€œ, the study focuses on the economic effects of the phenomenon of electrification of the powertrain in automobiles (e-mobility).
The researchers find that over the long run, e-mobility will lead to a lower GDP and employment level, and that the change in technology may lead â€œto 114,000 job cuts by the end of 2035â€. The report adds: â€œThe whole economy will lose about 0.6 % of the GDP. In the scenario we assume a share of only 23 percent of electric compared to all cars in 2035.â€
The following chart (Figure 28) shows the job losses as to industry sectors:

Chart shows change in number of German workers. The most workers will be lost in the vehicle production. Source: QuBe Project, Figure 28.


